20. Map Tiles and Points in Polygons

Chicago Data

Load the Data

For the last part of the semester we will be looking at a number of open data sets from the City of Chicago. We will load in several here:

comarea <- read_sf(file.path("data", "chicago_community_areas.geojson"))
ziparea <- read_sf(file.path("data", "zip_codes.geojson"))
socio <- read_csv(file.path("data", "census_socioeconomic.csv"))
medical <- read_csv(file.path("data", "chicago_medical_examiner_cases.csv.gz"))

Today, our focus on the spatial components of the dataset. The spatial data contains information about zip codes and community areas. Specifically, we will look at a set of records by the Medican Examiner’s office showing deaths they have investigated:

Advanced Spatial Data

Fixing Left Key Joins

When working on Project 3, we identified an issue with the way that R works when joining a spatial dataset and a non-spatial dataset. Unless the spatial data comes on the left (e.g., first), the spatial data attributes are lost. This is a problem if you later want to use spatial methods on the data. For example,

medical %>%
  left_join(ziparea, by = c("residence_zip" = "zip"))

I have now determined an easy solution. Simply use the function st_as_sf after performing the join. This will recreate the spatial metadata with the correct projection and spatial bounding coordinates:

medical %>%
  left_join(ziparea, by = c("residence_zip" = "zip")) %>%
  st_as_sf()

Creating Spatial Data

The medical records have a longitude and latitude attached to them based on the reported place of death. We can create a spatial object from this using the function st_as_sf. We will make sure that R knows these are longitude and latitude coordinates (crs = 4326) and that the lon/lat coordinates are not removed as columns in the data (remove = FALSE). After doing so, we can plot the data using geom_sf, which benefits from nice axis labels and the ability to do coordinate projections.

medical %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326, remove = FALSE) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(alpha = 0.01)

Using a low value for alpha shows where the majority of deaths reported by the Medical Examiner’s office are located.

Spatial Joins

The medical examiner data includes someone’s residence zip code. Because we have the spatial data about zip codes, it seems possible to compute those zip codes the actual death occured in. To do this, we need to use a method called a spatial join. There are many of these, some of which are quite complex, but the “points in polygon” method here is one of the most common.

The spatial_join function takes two datasets and joins them based on their spatial data. The datasets need to be in the same projection; here we convert ziparea to lat/lon coordinates. If we join the medical data, converted in spatial points data, into the zip code polygons, we will see which zip area each case occured in:

medical %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326) %>%
  spatial_join(st_transform(ziparea, 4326)) %>%
  select(residence_zip, zip)

Often these are the same, but there are many cases where the two zip codes do not match, as you will see in the Practice questions.

We can also run the join in the other direction, putting the polygon data on the left and the point data on the right. This results in a data set that still contains polygon data.

medical_geo <- medical %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326, remove = FALSE)

ziparea %>%
  st_transform(4326) %>%
  spatial_join(medical_geo) %>%
  select(residence_zip, zip)

I do not understand why this is the default, but notice that the variables in the second dataset might show up first in the table. You will see that there are some missing values in the dataset. These are zip codes that have no deaths occuring in them. By default, spatial_join uses a left spatial join; we can turn that off as follows:

ziparea %>%
  st_transform(4326) %>%
  spatial_join(medical_geo, left = FALSE) %>%
  select(residence_zip, zip)

There are many other kinds of spatial joins that we can run in R, but we will not go into details about them at this time. For example, we can combine two point datasets by matching up each point in one table with the closest point in the second table.

Distances

Let’s do one more final spatial manipulation of our data. We will make a spatial dataset with a single row corresponding to Millennium Park in downtown Chicago:

millennium_park <- tibble(lon = -87.6243107, lat = 41.882612) %>%
  st_as_sf(coords = c("lon", "lat"), crs = 4326)
millennium_park
## Simple feature collection with 1 feature and 0 fields
## Geometry type: POINT
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -87.62431 ymin: 41.88261 xmax: -87.62431 ymax: 41.88261
## Geodetic CRS:  WGS 84
## # A tibble: 1 × 1
##               geometry
## *          <POINT [°]>
## 1 (-87.62431 41.88261)

The reason for creating this data point is to compute the distance from all of the medical cases to the center of the park. The computation for this looks similar to the st_area function we saw last time. The results are returned in metres, which we convert to kilometres by dividing by 1000.

medical_geo %>%
  mutate(distance_mp = as.numeric(st_distance(geometry, millennium_park)) / 1000)

One application of this technique is to filter the data to only include points in a particular part of the world. Here, we look at just the deaths that occured near the Park:

medical_geo %>%
  mutate(distance_mp = as.numeric(st_distance(geometry, millennium_park)) / 1000) %>%
  filter(distance_mp < 3) %>%
  ggplot() +
    geom_sf(color = "grey90") +
    geom_sf(color = "orange", data = millennium_park) +
    geom_sf_label(
      label = "Millennium Park",
      color = "orange",
      data = millennium_park,
      nudge_y = -0.003
    )

You can see that it roughly maps out a circle (there is a lake to the East of the city).

Raster Graphics (Maptiles)

To wrap up our spatial methods, let’s look at something completely different. Rather than working with precise regions (vector data), it can often be useful to instead plot spatial data over a map. This map could be something similar to the maps used in Apple Maps or Google Maps. To start, let’s take only a set of points that are very close to the park:

medical_mp <- medical_geo %>%
  mutate(distance_mp = as.numeric(st_distance(geometry, millennium_park)) / 1000) %>%
  filter(distance_mp < 1.5)

In order to show these over a map, we simply use a scatter plot (NOT geom_sf) on top of a special layer called stat_maptiles. Note that the map times need to go first, otherwise they will be plotted on top of the points. We can set the opacity (alpha) of the times to make the data easier to see.

medical_mp %>%
  ggplot(aes(lon, lat)) +
    stat_maptiles(alpha = 0.3) +
    geom_point(aes(color = gun_related)) +
    theme_void()

There are many other options that you can tweak with the maptiles. See the link on the course website for more details.
